{"cursor":"10428","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox presenter\n| name = Alison Curtis image = birth_name = Alison Curtis birth_date =\n| birth_place = Kingston, Ontario, Canada death_date = death_place = show =\n| [[The Last Splash]], [[Phantom Feedback]] station = Today FM, Phantom 105.2\n| timeslot = Weekdays, 22:00 - 00:00 style = Disc jockey/chat jockey country =\n| Canada prevshow = web = [http://www.todayfm.com/Shows/Weekdays/Alison-\n| Curtis/BLOG.aspx Official site]\n}} 'Alison \"Ally\"' Curtis has claimed U2 producer, Daniel Elmarr, called\nher this on a \"going-away date\". Today FM. 18 December 2008. 'Curtis'\n(born 1 November 1977 in Kingston, Ontario, Canada) is a presenter of radio on\nIrish radio station Phantom\n105.2 [http://www.todayfm.com/showdj.asp?DJID=19723 Alison Curtis profile].\nToday FM. Retrieved 6 November 2008. and a respected figure on the Irish\nmusic scene. She presented The Last Splash on Sunday nights from 20:00 until\n22:00 and The Alison Curtis Show from 05:00 - 07:00.\n\nThe Last Splash and, later, The Alison Curtis Show, earned Curtis her three Best\nDJ Meteor nominations, though she narrowly lost out on the first two occasions\nto her Today FM colleague Ray D'Arcy and lost again in 2009, this time to her\nToday FM colleague Ray Foley. Curtis currently possesses her own television\nchannel [http://www.todayfm.com/Article.asp?id=909726 \"My TV Channel\"].\nRetrieved 6 November 2008.  and has written for [[Hot Press]].\n\nShe is married to Anton Hegarty, the former bassist for Future Kings of Spain.\n\nIn early March 2011, it was announced that Curtis, who is expecting her first\nchild, had left Today FM to return to Phantom FM, the radio station she\noriginally worked for before joining Today FM.\n","linknr":306,"url":"Alison_Curtis","recorded":1364038676,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Alison_Curtis&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Alison_Curtis&action=edit","//en.wikipedia.org/apple-touch-icon.png","//bi